## Representative figures

### Figure 1: First hit versus sustained capture

![First hit versus sustained capture](figure_01_first_hit_vs_sustained_capture.png)

**Figure:** B10.2-I2 separates first hit from sustained capture. Sustained capture peaks around an intermediate noise level, while at high noise first-hit probability can remain high even as sustained capture collapses.

---

### Figure 2: Canonical gate controls

![Canonical gate controls](figure_02_canonical_gate_controls.png)

**Figure:** Canonical L2 gate-control results. Closed-channel control suppresses sustained capture, while dynamic and open-channel controls retain finite-noise windows. The finite-noise window is therefore not simply a single-gate artifact.

---

### Figure 3: L2 versus I2 consistency audit

![L2 versus I2 consistency audit](figure_03_L2_vs_I2_consistency_audit.png)

**Figure:** Consistency audit comparing the canonical L2 dynamic_Rq implementation with the I2 dynamic_Rq result. The audit supports the reproducibility of the adopted B10.2 finite-noise sustained-capture window.

---

### Figure 4: Distance gating window

![Distance gating window](figure_04_distance_gating_window.png)

**Figure:** B10.1 distance-gating result. As initial distance increases, the finite-noise capture window contracts and the peak sustained-capture probability eventually declines.

